The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, together have 29 percent
The appreciable weakening of the two sides of the previous grand coalition and the significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties were brought about by the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly strong losses, with the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, shaking gravely.
Conversely, the election leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the country's Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest party with 29.8 percent of the vote, but loses 5.5 percent of the vote against the latest 2006 elections.
Worse still, the ÖVP, which loses almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of both of these major parties in Austria's post-war history and, especially for the Peoples, who provoked early elections, a literally disastrous result.
As recently as early July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the Peoples were well ahead of the SPÖ in their preferences.
But voters apparently punished them for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman and incumbent vice-chancellor, Wilhelm Molterer, was heard.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday at a special meeting of the party's bureau.
Such a development would probably facilitate the path to the still most likely way out of the election result, the renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) provisionally won 18 per cent and the BZÖ eleven per cent of the vote - the Social Democrats also voiced concerns about the repetition of the year 1999, when the People's Party agreed with populists (then the FPÖ was united, it was split from the BZÖ) in a joint government, which even triggered sanctions from the European Union.
Haider is clearly betting on this development, having already said he was ready to work with any party and envisions a return to Vienna for national politics.
The Green Party was still in parliament, but it lost slightly and fell between the Austrian political parties from third to fifth place.
Apparently, none of the other parties had overtaken the 4% threshold and did not make it to parliament.
