The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet we are missing something here - a virtual operator to make the classic ones cheaper.
He may not be absent for long.
We have written about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe in Europe many times.
Indeed, this was confirmed by ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
Following the European Commission's latest actions in the field of regulating roaming charges, this may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to go into battle.
It may sound paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetration to over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain about the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who has commented several times in the past, is often chimed in for them that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It's probably true that a classic operator with its own network doesn't seem to have much of a chance anymore (it would be hard to find frequencies for that matter anymore).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market brought about a significant price reduction, to which classical operators then had to respond.
At the same time, before the entry of the pike like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices in the UK as in the UK.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we don't have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, the operator has managed to recruit more than 100,000 customers and become the country's fifth largest operator.
At the same time, the financial group Penta, which owns U:fona among others, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, they only need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not entail relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators tend to profile themselves as low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a narrower service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as much cheaper as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobileiding in Poland shows, a bet on a novel target group can also be a pretty good move.
This operator specifically targets men.
"Chaired guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept could be caught up in our country.
Vodafone's press spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are founded.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Rather, the Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studničková, press spokesperson for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It implicitly confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are certainly not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hidden by the GTS Novera group for a long time, which would thus like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor to Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer field.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to move forward with some of them in the negotiations," says the group's press spokesperson, Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe there's a glimmer of better days.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be looking forward to perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room for a fully-fledged virtual operator to be created on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2 said in his comments to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also being invoked by other operators.
T-Mobil's press spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with O2's comments: "So far we have not seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to be further built."
He adds: "It is difficult for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we'd have to have a concrete agreement on the table to be considered in this short term."
Vodafone is more likely to be drawn to meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says: "By dealing with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of burden and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial in terms of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, a decrease in prices and thus a decline in their profits.
So why facilitate the emergence of such a competitor?
The fact that operators are at a point that they can pull together when an operator is involved, is also evidenced by the tussle over the creation of U:fona.
Perhaps the most pressure towards ČTÚ came at the time of the creation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
But now it is U:fon who is useful as an argument for not allowing a virtual operator to.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive mobile market environment was recently amplified by the entry of a fourth mobile operator to the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player would make high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the sheer disinterest of the Czech regulators is astonishing.
This is not just about the ČTÚ's position, which unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in competition in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his signature stance on the whole issue.
"A virtual operator's entry into the mobile market would be possible after a contract between a mobile operator and a virtual operator to lease the necessary infrastructure would be concluded.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential bidders was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations Department of the Office of the Office said in response to our inquiry.
The comments thus formulated will not be surprised by the representatives of the operators.
It is more from the Office, which is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position in the market, is more than a precarious one.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the country, where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services."
But apparently the pressure on the fair functioning of the market environment and the decline in prices are not among the interests of the OBR.
In fact, the shocking thing about the case is the touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is entirely self-evident.
Like the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is surely just a matter of chance and a fierce competition.
"The Office did not find signs of anti-competitive conduct in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, so it has a corresponding increased responsibility for its market conduct.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual operators are most likely missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his comments.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market in terms of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer a different perspective - the consent of the network operator is always required to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically, has a monopoly on its network.
So in a particular segment, it necessarily has to be dominant.
But even if we did not allow this argument, it should be at least a warning to the OBR that the three mobile operators are doing strikingly similarly.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The upload of responsibility to ČTÚ is then a rather common ploy in telecommunications, with which the OBR hands off the whole affair.
We've met him on several occasions like this.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of ČTÚ's powers to competition in telecommunications failed to enforce, although a number of experts promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the OHS must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's going to work when no one's looking
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-optional operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies issuing their own price lists for mobile telephony services, but they are only partially public.
They are usually companies engaged in multilevel marketing.
The likes of Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only the elect.
The magic is that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, they will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar reselling.
"If there were cases of which you are referring to, it could be a violation of the contractual terms that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová said in response to our question on the problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity will not be brought to the responsible people from mobile operators.
In the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is opposing such a procedure.
Indeed, they make not inconsiderable profits from the activities of these firms, and yet - unlike the actual virtual operators - do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out to possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, however, the services of these companies are used by only a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot dispose of it fully as ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is what should be at least strange to ČTÚ.
In addition, another question is being raised for the OBR.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the OBR has relatively strong powers to expose such an activity, and if it does not want to, it may not be content to explain to the operators that they have no idea about this and their terms of trade prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As the text has already fallen on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable decline in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, the classic operators sought to hinder their creation more or less.
The arguments used by them were virtually identical - too small, or, or, if too, a saturated market, service quality problems, etc.
But in developed countries, it was at these moments that regulators intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but in their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they then achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and another one was packed into it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are tossing the case around like a hot potato.
We cannot escape the impression from our experience that ambiguity in competencies is more than suited to them in these cases.
But let's not throw a gun in the toe.
If behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will really appear in our country soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the OBR to remain indifferent to the denial of (discrimination) of other bidders.
And we might stop calling for more than in the rest of Europe.
