"Auto bee" prevents rainfall
To advance the development of anti-accident technologies, Nissan was this time inspired by nature, specifically by bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes bee flying as a model, thus preventing collisions.
Such is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
Engineers of the Center for Technical Progress Nissan Motor Co. developed the robot in collaboration with the Centre for Progress in the scientific and technology research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology, R&D of the brand, BR23C is presented as an extension of the Nissan security shield's four zones.
The robot is designed to strengthen the ability to prevent precipitation in the brand's cars.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan's safety shield.
The most important, however, are the folded bee's eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, which the bee allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual feature, the engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder.
This records obstacles that are located up to a distance of two metres within a 180-degree radius of the BR23C, calculate the distance of the object and sends out the signal to the on-board microprocessor, which will immediately convert it to a collision warning.
"The moment the obstacle is recorded, the robot mimics the bee movements and immediately changes the direction of the wheel to the right or even larger angle to prevent the collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and the main engineer at this project.
The robot, unlike bees, cannot move upwards or downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited to two dimensions and to the direction that is made possible by rotating its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and options as for bees.
Nissan, therefore, in addition to acceleration and slowing down, used the rotation function to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The facility only needs to process the information every few seconds and act according to these data.
It does not require the preservation of information or logical intuitions from previous manoeuvres, which allows it to function without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
It may come as a surprise to you, but we don't talk about the gig or the mega at the memory.'
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for immediate precipitation prevention, a technology for which Nissan predicts use in serial cars in a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and lasts longer than lithium-ion.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to install the unit in the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to their destination, avoiding obstacles on the road.
