Héma-Québec was celebrating the tenth anniversary of its founding yesterday and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced, because Héma-Québec became one of the world's most reliable and efficient blood suppliers.
Above all, he has regained the public's confidence that was severely shaken after the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the national reserve of blood administered by the Department of Transfusion of the Canadian Red Cross was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and a wave of public reign, the Canadian government launched a public investigation in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not be repeated.
While Judge Krever delayed handing over the report, some of the provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee played out this role.
After the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to be farmed by Quebec, and a Canadian bloodstream to supply all the provinces and both territories.
"When Héma-Québec launched his activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was dismal.
By systematically trying to increase the safety of blood products and constant work in this area over the coming years, we have regained public confidence," he says, adding, proudly that in early 2008 Héma-Québek was already trusted by nearly 94% of the québean population.
Dr. Décaryová, however, does not lose sight of "trust is something very fragile."
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
"At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says the woman who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea whether this disease could spread through the blood.
We were therefore relying on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which, in the case of not knowing it and when the spread of a serious illness is at stake, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterised by the degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, the precautionary measure must be taken.
In April 1999, we therefore rejected blood from people who have been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that the disease was transmitted through the blood.
This episode has shown us that it made sense to follow the principle of prudence."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting the HIV virus: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) appeared on the market, allowing the presence of the virus itself to be detected in the donor blood, and not the presence of the antibodies on which the tests were based were used before.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the patient's infection moment and the moment when the first viruses can be detected by our blood techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without even knowing it and without us being able to figure out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of obtaining AIDS through blood transfusion.
The risk of getting blood from HIV contaminated with HIV is now exposed to one person in 12 million.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before anyone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission occurs via a blood product.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe the blood transfusion necessary to heal in complete peace," says the head of Héma-Québek's management.
"The challenge for the next decades is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what a disease-flag element may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by the stab of insects.
You need to be cautious at all times," Dr. Décaryová and stresses that in addition to the secure supply, Héma-Québec must also reckon with sufficient supply.
"ReOKs are growing because the population is aging.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of the Queens-offic permitted to donate."
Any healthy person at least 18 years old, corresponding to the admissibility criteria, but can only donate blood once every 56 days, that is to say six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not accepted on average because, for example, they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they visited the country where the mud chills are rampant, are excluded for one year.
"With these 3% we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortcomings are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, convincing people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unbridled today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are stored at the Héma-Québek, which also manages the only public bank of blood from the umbilical cord in Québek.
