Opinions - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discupue
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian Mining Company Barrick Gold.
With orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched the prosecution of three authors and a poor libel publishing house to incite a "transparent public debate" and is demanding six million of them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of prosecution for libel, but by law.
Not surprisingly, Garver is completely owing to this crucial distinction.
Or is it for Barrick Gold to bring to ruin anyone who would dare to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the process turns out to be, the author and publisher of the book Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend themselves and fight in a highly unbalanced fight with an army of attorneys supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, the tactics in these outstanding struggles often consist of ruining the defendants in order to enforce conciliation proceedings that will be fentling the opposing party and, moreover, afterdoing anyone who dared to pursue the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view to the whole thing.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate under normal circumstances consists in an exchange of ideas, rather than in baton blows.
Mining companies were therefore not enough to open their books, their documentation, and to establish a real debate through a newspaper, media, publications and funding of independent scientific teams that could shed light on the matter.
However, Barrick Gold does not seem to have any confidence in public opinion and rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of the book Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he could demand a "public debate" while despising the views of the same public?
This word in the vice-president's world seems to refer to only bold-paying attorneys, and not all Canadians; that is a rather narrowed concept.
In a democracy, even the lizigers have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public, who supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and consider the matter, but on the basis of a civilised exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant's mouth is to be clogged (in the framework of their prosecution of the "public debate" Barrick, by the way, has just given an official call to the authors of Noir Canada to officially inform them that they should stop using this term...).
Aside from the surreal speech of Garver, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university's freedom of research and the search for the truth that is essential for any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to quote trusted sources and to the debate about the facts and interpretations that itself underpin the basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that the rich firms of this world do not like without being subjected to repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have been created if it had followed the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has the right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's overreacting clearly shows that, despite what it claims, it has no appetite for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to introduce measures to limit such a type of unjustified prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Understand
Yesterday, the Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement on the biggest economic bailout plan since the Great Crisis of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use US$700 billion to hinder the financial crisis that has been clouding Wall Street for months must still be approved by both houses of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of its chosen representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money imposed, new arrangements for capturing the number of houses seized for non-perishable, as well as the right to monitor the level of wages paid to leading workers of rescued firms.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, following the end of the two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress and come to an agreement that is effective in the markets," said Bush administration official, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to make the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the crisis currently taking place on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"That's a crucial point: if we don't do it, the trauma, the chaos, and disruption of the Americans' daily lives will be enormous," said Jad Gregg, a Republican.
Over the past few hours, the negotiations have started to at maximum speed out of fear of the effect of further failure on investor state of mind.
The designated time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two US presidential candidates were invited to the negotiations later, and both were more likely to comment on the deal, but without neglecting to express their dissatisfaction with the need to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited the addition of an agreement on some of the measures, in particular the aim of which is to allow the owners of their residence to remain, and the wage measures for leading labor-ordered state-rescued firms.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate themselves on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the TV's waves.
His Republican rival, John McCain, who was questioned by another station as to whether to vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The coarse features I have read [show] that it is something that we will all have to digest and use to move on.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The $700bn plan aims to buy back doubtful claims and risky and non-negative assets of US financial institutions with taxpayer money.
The plan comes after a 14-month crisis sparked by the bursting of the housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in a cash freeze and the decomposition of banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of the first draft agreement last week is due to Republican MPs.
Ever since the Democrats agreed to the government's guarantee for some of the "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty, but not to buy them, there is a belief that the impasse is averted.
In an effort to approximate conflicting views in Congress, a measure has been added to the government that will be able to introduce new fees to help it get its deposit back if, as a result of the program, it has to take losses for five years.
The new plan envisages a first amount of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire stakes in rescued firms that will pay dividends to it in the event of a profit and which it will be able to resell when it is over.
The federal government will be able to delay seizure property logging procedures for the loans covered by the plan, as well as setting limits on the level of valuations and compensation paid to the executives of the affected firms.
The plan's architects would like to vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain that their plan will be green.
Yesterday, the vote in both the Republican and Democratic camp continued to rise against the project.
"It's very obvious that Washington can't hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Commission.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But earning money in the taxpayers is not the solution."
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen nicknamed the "Skeptics' Enforcement Committee," presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"The four hundred esteemed economics professors, among them the three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and to examine carefully which way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis was a world crisis.
Following the end of the emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced a partial nationalisation of Fortis, the banking group, for €11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from buying its competitor, which is on the verge of collapse since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) as a result of a crisis in risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, ranks among Europe's top 20 banks and among the top ten insurers.
"We will not lose this money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"In return, we get the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And that's what savers and households can appreciate in these uncertain times."
On the other side of the Channel, the British government, meanwhile, appears to have begun to nationalise another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing Bradford and Bringley loans, of which more than $41 billion ($75.5 billion) were loans to buy real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy out the branches and accounts of the British bank's clients.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the British government must nationalise since the start of the financial crisis.
