The psychology of trumping: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been uncovered by researchers in the field of neurology and economics at the University of New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to lag behind in the eBay auction competition, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
The research was used by an experimental auction to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers grated, the other group participated in a staged auction, with the active areas of the brain of the test subjects being investigated using the functional magnetic resonance imaging method.
In both games, the participants could have won the money, but in the game at the auction, an important element of which is to outmanecele, the whole found under the cerebral cortex, called striatum, began to work intensively in the loss.
This cerebrospheft region plays a role in the "self-referral" mechanism of the nervous system, among many other functions.
The unscrewing of the price is therefore, according to the researchers, to be explained by trying to avoid the stride reaction of the striata.
To shore up their theory, members of the economists' research team conducted a financial cross-sectional investigation.
In it, under different conditions, three groups were quoted against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the group were promised that if they emerged victorious, they would receive an extra $15 as a reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss its members lost that money as well.
The difference between the two groups was therefore all about one being emphasised by a win and another by losing.
The members of the group playing "anti-protest" were, however, willing to go higher than they were in the control and "victorious" group, which confirms the neurologists' hypothesis.
"These results cannot be deduced from any pre-existing economic theory.
For these, until now, they have explained the phenomena observable at auctions with the joys of victory and the avoidance of risk.
It was the neurological imaging methods that helped us resolve the contradiction between these two theories in such a way that we have now come to a third explanation," stated Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of Economics at the University of New York University.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, while in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only 7,000 of them are being treated. The cause of this is that the sick often do not know they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the poo to formulate the name of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, the liver and jaundice inflammation are characterised, but the agents of the disease and the diseases they cause for each other differ from each other.
Hepatitis virus is spreading in two main ways depending on the cause of the disease: hepatitis A and E of the digestive system (for example, by infected foods, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses of blood and bodily fluids (sperma, theatrial secretions, spiches).
In any case, travellers should be protected by vaccinating A and B, and there is no vaccine against the C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after taking the infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, urges to vomit.
Then, on the skin and the whites of the eyes, the egg yolk forms, the lightened stool and darkens the urine. The treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people die worldwide from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that an estimated one in ten of the infected is treated with medication.
hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of the infected are not even aware of their illness, the agents of the disease are destroying liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms do not come in many cases until 20-30 years.
That is why early prevention, the conduct of regular depotism, is very important.
In three groups, the disease occurs a lot more often than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, between drug users and people with tattoos.
Currently, the projected global number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
As the disease can already be shown by a routine laboratory examination, the person should contact his or her general practitioner if he or she notars any sign of unknown origin.
When detected early, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the organism to prevent contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, which was organised by the organisations representing the sick for the world for the first time in 2004.
